---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

// ProfilePage/Person schema — establishes Saneesh as the author entity and
// links his identity across the web (personal site, LinkedIn, GitHub).
const authorSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'ProfilePage',
  mainEntity: {
    '@type': 'Person',
    name: 'Saneesh Narikutty Pacha',
    alternateName: 'Saneesh',
    url: 'https://saneesh.net',
    image: 'https://distilledcs.org/images/saneesh-narikutty-pacha.jpg',
    description: 'Creator of Distilled CS, an open framework for Customer Success maturity. Around ten years of experience across Customer Success teams.',
    sameAs: [
      'https://saneesh.net',
      'https://www.linkedin.com/in/saneesh-np/',
      'https://github.com/saneeshnp',
    ],
  },
};
---

<BaseLayout title="About" description="The story behind Distilled CS: why Saneesh built an open, vendor-neutral framework to help Customer Success teams see where they stand and improve their strategy stage by stage." structuredData={[authorSchema]}>

  <div class="container about-page">

    <header class="page-header">
      <h1 class="page-title">About Distilled CS</h1>
      <p class="page-subtitle">Why I built it, and how it can help your CS team.</p>
    </header>

    <div class="page-body">
      <p class="about-lead">
        Hi, thank you for visiting Distilled CS! I'm Saneesh, and I built Distilled CS with one goal in mind: help CS teams see their gaps clearly and give them a structured way to improve their strategy.
      </p>

      <p>
        Today, there is no standard framework to assess the <a href="/customer-success-maturity-model/">maturity of a customer success team</a> or organization. Having worked in the industry for close to 10 years across different customer success teams, I have realized that customer success teams often need to shift strategy to operate at the optimum level, and without a way to measure where they stand, that shift is not easy.
      </p>

      <p>
        To understand what is the best strategy for your CS organization, you first need to understand where you are, and that's exactly what the <a href="/assess/">Distilled CS assessment</a> tries to do. It measures your team across various domains to give you a score that tells you where you stand.
      </p>

      <p>
        The goal of this framework is not to give a precise consultation. That's not possible as customer success teams operate very differently across customer segments and products. My goal is to provide a solid starting point for teams to assess where they are. I also want this to be a small platform with all the guidance available in one place to help you get there, stage by stage.
      </p>

      <p>
        You can start with the CS maturity assessment and go further from there. All the recommendations that are provided here are supported by detailed <a href="/customer-success-metrics/">metrics</a>, <a href="/customer-success-playbooks/">playbooks</a>, <a href="/checklist/">checklists</a> and more.
      </p>

      <p>
        Distilled CS is open source because I want it to be fully transparent, and it is <a href="/contribute/">open to your ideas</a>. If something here doesn't match your experience, I would love to hear it. <a href="https://github.com/saneeshnp/distilled-cs/issues/new/choose" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open an issue on GitHub</a> or share what worked for your team. For now, you can find Distilled CS on <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/company/distilled-cs/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">LinkedIn</a> and <a href="https://github.com/saneeshnp/distilled-cs" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">GitHub</a>, and I hope to expand more in the future.
      </p>

      <div class="about-signoff">
        <p class="about-signoff-name">Saneesh</p>
        <p class="about-signoff-links">
          <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/saneesh-np/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">LinkedIn</a>
          <a href="https://x.com/saneeshnp" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">X</a>
          <a href="https://saneesh.net" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Website</a>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>

</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .about-page {
    padding-block: 3rem 5rem;
    max-width: 42rem;
    margin-inline: auto;
  }

  .page-header {
    text-align: center;
    margin-bottom: 3rem;
  }

  .page-title {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: clamp(2.25rem, 5vw, 3.25rem);
    color: var(--color-text-primary);
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
    letter-spacing: -0.03em;
  }

  .page-subtitle {
    font-size: clamp(1rem, 1.5vw, 1.125rem);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .page-body {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 1.25rem;
  }

  .about-lead {
    font-size: 1.1875rem;
    line-height: 1.65;
    color: var(--color-text-primary);
    font-weight: 500;
  }

  .page-body > p:not(.about-lead) {
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  .page-body > p a {
    color: var(--color-accent);
  }

  .page-body > p a:hover {
    color: var(--color-accent-hover);
  }

  .about-signoff {
    margin-top: 0.5rem;
    padding-top: 1.5rem;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .about-signoff-name {
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-text-primary);
    margin-bottom: 0.375rem;
  }

  .about-signoff-links {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    align-items: baseline;
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
  }

  .about-signoff-links a {
    color: var(--color-accent);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .about-signoff-links a:hover {
    color: var(--color-accent-hover);
    text-decoration: underline;
  }

  /* Separator rides with its link (as a ::before), so it can never be
     orphaned at a line end on wrap; inline-block keeps it off the hover
     underline and baseline-aligned with the link text. */
  .about-signoff-links a + a::before {
    content: "|";
    display: inline-block;
    margin: 0 0.75rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
  }
</style>
